    "body": "Here is an example:\r\nI am calling forge verify-contract from a bash script:\r\n\r\n`forge verify-contract --watch --chain \"$NETWORK\" \"$ADDRESS\" \"$FULL_PATH\" -e \"${!API_KEY}\"\r\n`\r\n\r\nThe NETWORK parameter has the value \"okx\" which has never been a problem before. All of a sudden it fails and it shows me this list of \"allowed\" chains. \r\n\r\nThe same happened when I used \"bsctest\" (cause as you can see, there is only \"bsc-testnet\" in the list so it wants exactly that name. \r\n\r\n<img width=\"2558\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://github.com/foundry-rs/foundry/assets/77058885/4d2ad1c2-abd9-47db-b3ea-2b0c2907e3be\">\r\n\r\n\r\nNow with bsctest it was easy, cause there was a corrected name that I could use. \r\nAccording to the --help info, I can also use the chainId. But when I try that (with chainId 66 and passing a valid API key from https://www.oklink.com) it throws an error \"ETHERSCAN_API_KEY must be set\".\r\nI also tried to call forge verify-contract with an env-variable called ETHERSCAN_API_KEY from bash like this:\r\n`ETHERSCAN_API_KEY=${!API_KEY} forge verify-contract --watch --chain \"$CHAIN_ID\" \"$ADDRESS\" \"$FULL_PATH\" -e \"${!API_KEY}\"`\r\nand that didnt work either (same error)\r\n\r\n\r\nDo you have any suggestions how to deal with this?  ",
